					<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Not quite. As children develop internal control over their emotions, they can gain control over their behavior. Caregivers can support this new independence by providing guidance for children in how to handle their environment. To do so, adults should include the rationale for a rule so that children understand the reason the rule needs to be followed. For example, Zachary's mother could say: “It is a rule in our family that everyone stay at the table until we are all finished eating. This makes each person feel like an important part of the family.” &lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;The goal for developing self-regulation is not to force the child to comply with external rules but to help them develop internal control for understanding and respecting guidelines.&lt;/P&gt;</content>
